`crates/steno/src/expand/` turns a parsed dictionary (`Entry` records) into fully-resolved `TypedEntry` steno steps, ready for rendering by both the enumerative pipeline and the C++-facing lookup replay in `infinite/`. Depending on this module gets you `expand_dict()`: the sole external entry point, plus `TypedEntry`/`ExpandedEntry` as the shared intermediate/final record shapes.

The pipeline is a strict three-pass sequence, and each pass's output format is a hard contract for the next: `counts.rs` resolves `%d`/`%[…%]`/computed chunks into `ExpandedEntry` (still carrying unresolved `%t`/`%b`/braces/landings — later passes must not assume otherwise), `append.rs` fills `%t` slots using the pool built by `types.rs` (via `fill.rs`'s substitution primitives) into `TypedEntry` with `terminal` set per-entry, then two whole-batch correction passes run in order: `family.rs` clears `terminal` on any entry that's a strict stroke-prefix of another (fixing a blind spot `append.rs` can't see one-entry-at-a-time), and `lineflag.rs` doubles eligible terminal multi-stroke entries into one-liner variants. `family.rs` must run after all entries are typed; `lineflag.rs` depends on `family.rs`'s corrected `terminal` flags being final. `@type`-flagged entries are consumed by `types.rs` to build the append pool and never themselves appear in `expand_dict`'s output.

Shared invariants across the batch: strokes are always `/`-joined segments, and mutations to a stroke's first vs. last segment are semantically distinct throughout (`counts.rs` merges into the *last* segment for bank keys; `lineflag.rs` adds `U` to the *first* segment for one-liner eligibility, a steno-chording constraint, not a style choice). `TypeOptions`/`TypeDef` (from `types.rs`) and `Chunk` variants (from `crate::parse`) are consumed identically by `append.rs` and `fill.rs` — a field/variant change there requires updating both in lockstep.

`infinite/` is a separate consumer of Pass A's `ExpandedEntry` and Pass B's type-pool machinery, replaying type-filling on demand for O(strokes) lookup rather than full enumeration; its D12 slot-fill format must stay byte-identical to an independently-maintained C++ implementation.